					<div class="content-intro-text">
						<h1>How sustainable are biofuels? Between common curiosity and confronting interests</h1>
													<p class="author"><strong>Author:</strong>
								Bart de Steenhuijsen Piters</p>
																								
													<p class="date"><strong>Date:</strong>
							16/04/2007</p>
																									<p class="intro">Introduction:</p>
							<p>







 




  
  

	
	<a href="/var/knowledge/storage/images/media/images/dossiers_s_t_issues_in_perspective/biofuel_jatropha/224885-1-eng-GB/biofuel_jatropha.jpg" rel="lightbox[]" >	
	  </a>
	
	
	
	
  	






	 
  





	With the exception of Nigeria and Cameroon and Trinidad &amp; Tobago, all ACP countries are dependent on imported petroleum fuels for energy purposes. The world market prices of fossil fuels are unpredictable and likely to continue to increase in the foreseeable future. Can biofuels provide a long-term alternative by using locally produced renewable alternatives at a relatively constant cost? What are the gains at micro and macro levels, and what are the constraints and negative effects that we can expect from large-scale biofuel production? Can biofuels be produced on a sustainable basis and what would be required to achieve that goal?</p>
						
						
						
						<br/>&nbsp;
					</div> 
					<br class="cl">
				</div> 
				 
			
				<div id="content-item">
											<div class="box-content">
							<a class="storylist" href="/layout/set/print/content/view/full/4409">Print</a>
																				</div> 
						<br class="cl">
		
					 
	
				</div> 
			
				<div id="main-content" class="content view">					

	                          
			

	<!-- BEGIN BODY TEXT -->	
	
			<div class="stdtext">	
			
<p>Biofuels are products that can be processed into liquid fuels for either transport or heating purposes. Bioethanol and biodiesel are two of the most common forms of biofuels. Others include biomethanol, biodimethylether and biogas. Bioethanol is produced from crops such as sugarcane, corn, beet, wheat and sorghum. A new generation of ‘lignocellulosic’ bioethanol also includes a range of forestry products such as short rotation coppices and energy grasses. Biodiesel is made from seeds such as rapeseed, sunflower, soy, palm, coconut or Jatropha. New biodiesel technologies synthesize diesel fuels from wood and straw to a gasification stage (Annie Dufey, IIED, 2007).</p><p>Large scale biofuel production started as early as 1970 in Brazil, where the sugar industry developed successfully but met serious market distortions due to subsidy regimes in western economies. Transformation of sugar into bioethanol served various purposes, from substitution of fossil fuel imports and reduction of foreign exchange flows to protection of the domestic sugar industry. It is only recently that biofuels are receiving worldwide consideration. Reasons for the global interest include the potential of biofuels to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, reduce dependency on fossil fuels and mitigate against the high oil prices of 2005 and 2006. Biofuels and biofuel-based industries can generate income opportunities for local farmers and may even affect the market prices of agricultural commodities for which competition in demand increases, such as sugar, maize and soya.</p><p>The trade in carbon credits is already having a positive impact on the economics of biofuel-based industries. </p><p>Rudy Rabbinge, professor in sustainable development and food security at the Wageningen University, concluded in his presentation on 18 December 2006 for the Koninklijke Landbouwkundige Vereniging that current biofuel crops are not efficient energy producers and require vast surfaces of arable land that will not be available for other purposes, such as food production. He strongly pleaded for the development of C4 crops (trees and biomass producers) that are more efficient energy converters, limited production of crops such as Jathropha in developing countries, and the valorization of waste.</p><p>Other critics of global promotion of biofuel production refer also to the vast space that biobased economies would require. Biomass produces, on average, 20.000 kWh per hectare, wind 150.000 kWh per hectare and solar approximately 400.000 kWh per hectare (Vollenbroek, Frans, in: Milieu, May 2006). Can we promote massive biofuel production if we take into account global population growth, fast growing human consumption and our concern for biodiversity and natural resources? </p><p>Various authors have indicated that biofuel crops need agricultural inputs, such as industrial fertilizers which require fossil energy for their production and transportation. This would negatively affect the gross contribution by biofuels to reducing atmospheric carbon dioxide.</p><p>Estimates range from 0.2 – 1.3 liters of fossil fuel per liter of biofuel (Katan, Rabbinge and van Swaaij in: Financieel Dagblad 6 July 2006). These estimates mainly refer to intensive production systems in Europe and the USA. Production systems in ACP countries are generally less intensive in terms of input use. Biofuel crops in ACP countries generally consume less industrial fertilizers and depend more on the nutrients available in the soil. This immediately raises questions regarding the sustainability of biofuel production: will extraction of soil nutrients for fuel production result in the depletion of natural resources?</p><p>The new global interest in biofuels has already been translated into rapidly expanding international biofuel markets. A growing number of industrialized and developing countries have introduced policies to increase the proportion of biofuels within their energy portfolio. With the Kyoto Protocol’s recent entry into force and the worldwide implementation of national targets for biofuels, it is expected that in the next 20 years global biofuel production will quadruple, accounting for about 10 percent of world motor fuel (IEA, International Energy Agency, April 2004). In the EU it is clear that priority is given to the development of C4 crops and use of agro industrial waste. Public – private investments are done in technology development for this purpose. This policy is not yet observed in the ACP countries.</p><p>In ACP countries and notably in Sub-Saharan Africa, the new initiatives tend to concentrate on biodiesel production based on oilseed crops. A previously neglected plant, Jatropha, is among the most promising species. In a Newsweek article of Feb. 19, 2007 issue - Jatropha was referred to as “the Cinderella of the plant world: throw a seed in the poorest soil on the planet, and up comes a bush that will likely last 50 years”. According to Newsweek, Norwegian, Indian and British companies are racing to buy up or lease enormous swaths of African land for Jatropha plantations. U.K.-based D1 Oils has bought 20,000 hectares in Malawi and 15,000 hectares in Zambia. India's IKF Tech has requested government leases for a total of 150,000 hectares of land in Swaziland, Mozambique and South Africa. Worldwide Bio Refineries, a U.K. firm, has 40,000 hectares set aside for production in Nigeria, with planting to begin in May. Countries such as Mali and Mozambique have initiated special task forces for the promotion of Jathropha.</p><p>The public opinion on the use of palm oil as biofuel is becoming more and more critical in view of evidence that tropical forests are wasted for the establishment of palm plantations. The first claims that production of biofuel has boosted the consumer prize of maize in Mexico, thus affecting the food security of poor urban households, are published in newspapers. How will the creation of large scale plantations of Jathropha affect smallholders and livestock keepers in Sub-Saharan Africa? How ‘green’ are these biodiesel production systems? Should not Jathropha production to a greater extent be integrated into the existing farming systems and achieve ‘scale’ through the involvement of hundreds of thousands of smallholders?</p><p>From all debates and research reports one thing is clear: biofuels serve many purposes and even more interests. A debate on the future of biofuels results in a confrontation of ideologies and intellectual hemispheres that are usually separated from each other. We must conclude that the realization of environmental, economic and social benefits of biofuels is not straightforward. The trade-offs need to become clearer to all stakeholders. Pragmatic private initiatives seem to merit economic interests and may even result in negative social and environmental impacts. As Annie Dufey of IIED states (2007): developing countries need to seize the opportunities and appreciate the costs of the biofuels market, identifying those that are most suitable for the achievement of their sustainable development goals. The scale of biofuels production matters for achieving economies of scale. But large-scale models run the risk of squeezing out small-scale producers and the associated sustainable development benefits. Moreover, it seems that the EU follows a domestic policy of investments in technology that limits the use of land resources, while in ACP countries private companies are ready to turn vast acreages of apparent bare land into biofuel cultivation. Harmonization of biofuel policies at a global level and optimization of public and private investments for the sake of sustainable development are urgently needed.</p><p><b> <i>Bart de Steenhuijsen Piters</i> (PhD) - Area Leader Sustainable Economic Development Royal Tropical Institute, KIT Development, Policy &amp; Practice</b> </p><p><b>References</b> </p><p>Dufey, Annie (2007), IIED. International <i>trade in biofuels: Good for development? And good for environment?,</i> International Institute for Environment and Development.</p><p>IEA (Aoril 2004) ‘ <i>Biofuels for Transport An International Perspective’</i>, International Energy Agency, Paris.</p><p>Katan, Rabbinge and van Swaaij (2006), ‘Toekomst voor biodiesel is illusie; Problemen met biodiesel’ in: <i>Financieel Dagblad, 6 July 2006</i> </p><p>Palmer, Karen (2007) The Cinderella Plant. <a href="http://www.keepmedia.com/pubs/Newsweek/2007/02/19/2779484?&amp;pbl=215" target="_blank"> <i>Newsweek article of Feb. 19, 2007</i> </a> </p><p>Rabbinge, Rudy (2006) <i>Bieten, Bintjes of Brandhout: Wereldlezing Biofuel</i><a href="http://www.klv.nl/debatten_KLV/Presentatie%20Rabbinge%20werelddebat%20Biodiesel%2018%20dec%202006.pdf" target="_blank"> </a>, Koninklijke Landbouwkundige Vereniging Wageningen, 18 december 2006</p><p>Vollenbroek (2006) Frans, Geen grenzen aan de groei; ‘Bio-based Economy’ een doodlopende weg, in: <i>Milieu, May 2006</i> </p>
		</div>
		
	<!-- END BODY TEXT -->
		
			
		
	
	
			
				

		<strong class="date_small">16/04/2007</strong>
